The '''Slade Professorship of Fine Art''' is the oldest professorship of [[art]] at the universities of [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and [[University College, London|London]].
==History== The chairs were founded concurrently in 1869 by a bequest from the art collector and philanthropist [[Felix Slade]], with [[studentship]]s also created in the University of London. The studentships allowed for the creation of the [[Slade School of Art]], now part of [[University College London]], whose Director holds the Slade Professorship. They are normally therefore a practising artist.
The chair at Oxford is a visiting professorship, with duties restricted to a series of eight public lectures per year, on the "History, Theory, and Practice of the Fine Arts",<ref>[http://www.ox.ac.uk/media/global/wwwoxacuk/localsites/currentvacancies/furtherparticularsforprofessorships/sladeprofs.pdf "Slade Professorship of Fine Art"], University of Oxford, retrieved 21 June 2017</ref> to which four seminars have been added from 2011. The professorship is associated with [[All Souls College, Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.admin.ox.ac.uk/fp/sladeprofs.shtml Oxford University website]</ref> The bequest was also indirectly responsible for the foundation of the [[Ruskin School of Drawing]] in Oxford, which was financed by the first Oxford Professor, [[John Ruskin]], who announced his intention in his inaugural lecture "to the general dismay of his listeners".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OfjghCa3CnMC&pg=PA508&dq=Slade+Professorship+of+Fine+Art+London&ei=vrQSS_WmCI3mMO76lP0K#v=onepage&q=Slade%20Professorship%20of%20Fine%20Art%20London&f=false Official History of Oxford University, Vol VII]</ref>
The Cambridge Lectures are also a series of eight public lectures by a visiting professor. The Oxford and Cambridge professors are most often [[art historian]]s or critics, but some artists have held the posts, especially at Oxford. The lectures are often subsequently published in a book version.
